{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/vitiligo/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"cfca1785-6f25-546b-8fba-a9bb5ec8bc4f","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field bf9414f0-9322-4776-b32b-618573f8ea18 --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field bf9414f0-9322-4776-b32b-618573f8ea18 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 2f785a4b-98ca-43f0-914c-39fbc06130f6 --><!-- begin field 5a3e9a3f-8c2f-4e10-8455-5b18a6957c3f --><p><strong>Vitiligo is the most common depigmenting skin disorder </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Bergqvist, 2020</a>]<strong>. The reported prevalence of vitiligo in the literature varies according to the study population and geographical location of the studies.</strong></p><ul><li>A review of 50 epidemiological studies found the worldwide prevalence of vitiligo in the general population ranged from 0.06 to 2.28%, and was 0.0–2.16% in children and young people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Kruger, 2012</a>].<ul><li>Other studies cite the worldwide prevalence as about 0.5–2% of the population [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Ezzedine, 2016</a>].</li><li>A Chinese meta-analysis of 103 international studies found the pooled prevalence of vitiligo from 82 population- or community-based studies was 0.2%, and from 22 hospital-based studies was 1.8% [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Zhang, 2016</a>].<ul><li>A higher prevalence was reported in African studies and in females.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li>Vitiligo onset increases through the first two decades of life. It is uncommon in children younger than 2 years [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Ezzedine, 2016</a>].<ul><li>A prospective observational study of dermatology presentations to a tertiary centre outpatient department in Nepal (n = 1086) found that 2% of children were affected by vitiligo [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Shrestha, 2012</a>].</li><li>A systematic review of treatments for vitiligo in children states about 50% of people have onset of disease before the age of 20 years [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">de Menezes, 2016</a>].</li></ul></li><li>Prevalence is evenly distributed between the two sexes, and there is no difference in frequency according to skin type or ethnicity [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Plensdorf, 2017</a>].<ul><li>Expert opinion in a review article notes that some studies support a predominance of females affected in the youngest age groups, with similar incidence between the two sexes in older age groups [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Ezzedine, 2016</a>].</li><li>Variations in reported prevalence rates may be due to higher reporting where social and cultural stigma are common, or where lesions are more evident in darker-skinned people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Bergqvist, 2020</a>].</li></ul></li><li>A Brazilian retrospective observational study based in a paediatric hospital (n = 119 children with vitiligo) found [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Marinho, 2013</a>]:<ul><li>42% of cases were male and 58% were female.</li><li>40% of cases occurred between 6 and 10 years of age; 11% occurred in those under 2 years.</li><li>34% of cases were generalized type; 29% were segmental type; 21% indeterminate type; 13% acrofacial type; and 3% mucosal type.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 5a3e9a3f-8c2f-4e10-8455-5b18a6957c3f --><!-- end item 2f785a4b-98ca-43f0-914c-39fbc06130f6 -->","topic":{"id":"72501cc1-fbf6-5c3a-bfc1-1a2d865f7dff","topicId":"85a32b0f-cf7a-41c9-9dd8-caed21004663","topicName":"Vitiligo","slug":"vitiligo","lastRevised":"Last revised in April 2020","chapters":[{"id":"237f05d1-6751-5abf-98b0-af49db55e1b3","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e51e2938-3e89-53a6-9251-b0376a90be4d","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"5c590af0-29e5-5be3-958d-02f67350d529","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"aee2331c-c78c-5c0d-ba9a-c974cfb039ae","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"8afc6e46-c250-5eb3-85a1-355d3e18ee65","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"78bbc5cd-9e73-55fb-b421-d718417be14a","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"1a4f8e76-7634-54ba-8849-3051a448dccc","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"65dbcf54-b53e-54e8-a2fe-a07b8aae49f2","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"ba868062-b333-5694-90cb-1b24ed0d9c11","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"1912341a-6cf7-5d2a-b20d-cb4f55308c36","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"05992da2-cc78-5880-8307-5a5f8e4cc4da","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"30dc5858-bfd0-5918-b331-9067d9743f12","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"33d1fc44-e925-5b20-982d-7e60d75465ea","fullItemName":"Background information","slug":"background-information","subChapters":[{"id":"c23ed46f-6f85-51ef-9f34-aea63f9aea9e","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition"},{"id":"cfca1785-6f25-